Identifying ComponentsFeatures ($X$ / Inputs): Study Hours, Sleep Hours, Attendance %. These are the variables we believe cause the change in the score.
Label ($Y$ / Target): Exam Marks. This is the specific value we want our model to eventually predict.
Observation Unit: Each row represents one unique Student Instance.

Predicting the Relationship
By looking at the data, we can predict a Positive Linear Correlation.
The Logic: As "Study Hours" increases, "Exam Marks" also tends to increase.
The Nuance: Notice that "Sleep Hours" often decreases as "Study Hours" gets very high, suggesting a "Diminishing Return" where studying too much might hurt performance if sleep is sacrificed.

Learning OutcomesFeature Selection: Learning that not all data is useful. (e.g., a "Student Name" is a feature, but it doesn't help predict a grade, so we exclude it from the ML logic).
Understanding Causality: Distinguishing between the Independent Variable (Hours) and the Dependent Variable (Marks).
Data Quality Intuition: Realizing that real-world data is rarely perfect—there are often "noise" factors (like sleep or luck) that affect the final label.
Hypothesis Framing: Training your brain to look for patterns ($Y = mX + c$) before you even start writing code.
